column1: Before 2 October 2021, will the UN General Assembly recognize delegates from the National Unity Government (NUG) as representing Myanmar for the 76th General Assembly session?
column6: ['Foreign Policy', 'Security and Conflict', 'Non-US Politics']

Triggered by a comment by @MCowley below, on "optimism" and "specific recognition from the UNGA", and just hours before the question closes (with the crowd still at 0%), let me wrap-up and summarize for one last time the evidence that I think shows that the question has already been resolved as a "Yes".

While I like some people's optimism, the question seems to require specific recognition from the UNGA and as it states "attendance alone would not count", as noted in their example of 2 rival delegations from Venezuela both sitting in session.

Here is Kyaw Moe Tun in an interview published today, Sep 30, by The Irrawaddy (which refers to him as "Myanmar UN ambassador" in the title): https://www.irrawaddy.com/in-person/interview/international-pressure-essential-in-war-against-junta-myanmars-un-ambassador.html
Based on the evidence of @ctsats
Most probably, and for the time frame of the question, this has been resolved by now, as laid out in my previous rationale https://www.gjopen.com/comments/1335986 .

The United Nations General Assembly will consider the credentials of all representatives of all member States, but an issue can be raised as to whether the representative is accredited by Government actually in power. This is pertinent in this case. Membership in the Organisation, in accordance with its charter is open to all peace-loving States and that they are able to carry out such obligations. The NUG has announced a ‘peoples defensive war against the junta and so abandoning the non-violent tactics of Suu Kyi as adopted during her house arrest. This is perceived as an overt call to violence with a potential outbreak of civil war, which can hardly be countenanced by the UN and its charter. Member States are not minded in recognising an authority ‘in exile’ as the legitimate government, given the difficulty in defining ‘legitimate’.

In an exclusive interview in Myanmar magazine Mizzima (https://mizzima.com/article/ambassador-u-kyaw-moe-tun-speaks-mizzima), Kyaw Moe Tun confirms the plan first reported in Foreign Policy and later in the Wall Street Journal (https://www.gjopen.com/comments/1335986); some relevant excerpts:

According to the State Department and the US Embassy in Bhurma (sic), Kyaw Moe Tun is still today (Sep 24) the Myanmar Permanent Representative to the UN: https://twitter.com/usembassyburma/status/1441184315052679168 https://www.state.gov/counselor-chollets-meeting-with-burmese-representatives/

There seems to be no denying the Kyaw Moe Tun is the delegate of the NUG. And to date it seems that he is still recognised as the permanent representative to the UN according to the official UN Protocol and Liaison Service: https://bluebook.unmeetings.org/ , which currently shows Kyaw Moe Tun as the PR (choose "Member States maintaining permanent missions in Headquarters" in the 1st pull-down menu and "Myanmar" in the 2nd) Even though he is not attending the General Debate this week due to some diplomatic wrangling. https://archive.is/gdsp5

I have made a couple of mistakes to date. Deferring the vote would not result in accepting the incumbent. A deferred vote would leave the incumbent in place as a provisional delegate. I don't believe that this would result in this question being resolved yes. I do note that the UNs condemnation of the coup is a very strong message so if a vote is held then I think it will go the way of NUG but I suspect it will be deferred. Deferral might be used to hurry along the Junta into sorting out the situation. I am no longer confident that I am not about to get a stonking great big briar score. Darn

Admission is subject to security council recommendation which can be vetoed. Given that two countries are Authoritarian I do not see them likely stand up for an exiled democratic government. China has a little more in the game than ideology, a hamstrung democracy with strong economic ties served them better than an authoritarian economically inept government but now that it has happened they will prefer whoever has the best chance of keeping order and preventing a failed state on their border. I think China and Russia will veto their admission

The question hinges on Kyaw Moe Tun staying with the UN it seems. He was appointed permanent representative to the UN in 2018 but has been with the Permanent Mission of Myanmar to the UN since 2012. This means he has momentum and reputation. He is currently serving in the New York office of the UN.

According to this article (https://www.aljazeera.com/news/2021/8/1/six-months-after-myanmar-coup-battle-for-diplomatic-recognition), the status-quo is the most likely outcome. The UN in the past has given credence to those on the ground as well which would disfavour NUG.
Junta will make enough democratic concessions just to avert NUG recognition. Combined with this being a proxy-conflict as well as int'l habit: No.

The official UN line is: ‘Delegates represent their countries, speak and vote on behalf of their country at the UN General Assembly, unless a politician of higher rank is present. They are appointed by their countries and follow the interests of the government they serve’.
